            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Valerio is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fading working-class soul. Born and raised in the Excelsior District, he was the only child of a Filipino immigrant mother, a compassionate and perpetually tired nurse at SF General, and a second-generation Italian-American father who worked as an ironworker on the city\u2019s evolving skyline. His childhood was a vibrant mix of adobo and lasagna, of the Lumina theatre on Ocean Avenue and mass at Corpus Christi. He learned early on that community was not an abstract concept, but the web of neighbors who shared food, watched each other\u2019s kids, and spoke a dozen different languages on the same block.\n\nHis path wasn\u2019t always clear. He enrolled at San Francisco State University with a vague notion of going into business, but a sociology class changed his trajectory. It gave him the language to understand the systemic inequities he\u2019d witnessed his whole life. The true turning point came when his father was injured on the job, and Marco watched his parents navigate a labyrinthine bureaucracy of healthcare and workers' compensation. Seeing their struggle ignited a fire in him, cementing his decision to work for the community rather than a corporation. After graduating, he started as a case manager at a Mission-based non-profit and spent two decades working his way up.\n\nNow, at 47, Marco is the Program Director, overseeing initiatives that provide vital services to the city\u2019s most vulnerable. His 2.5-mile commute on the 14-Mission bus takes him from his modest apartment in the Inner Richmond to the heart of the community he serves. He lives a life of routine and purpose: early mornings with strong coffee, long days managing budgets and mentoring staff, and evenings often spent attending community board meetings.\n\nAmicably divorced for five years, his most important relationship is with his 20-year-old daughter, a student at his alma mater. They share a weekly dinner, a ritual that grounds him. His hopes are not for wealth or recognition, but for sustainability\u2014for the grants to come through, for the programs to expand, and for the city he loves to find a way to preserve its compassionate core. He dreams of one day securing a permanent home for his organization, a stable anchor for a community adrift in a sea of change."
